description: Cislunar Autonomous Positioning System Technology Operations and Navigation Experiment (CAPSTONE) is a cubesat mission that will serve as a precursor for the planned Gateway. Will use Photon to place CAPSTONE on a trajectory to the Moon. (Wikipedia)

name: SiriusXM 8
description: SpaceX will launch a high power broadcasting satellite for SiriusXM satellite radio. The satellite was built by SSL, and it will communicate in the S-band. The satellite will replace the XM 4 satellite.

name: NASA Crew-2
description: Second operational flight of Crew Dragon for Commercial Crew Program (3rd flight carrying astronauts). Will transport four astronauts to the ISS who will spend 6 months aboard the ISS. Starting on USCV-3 SpaceX is allowed to fly astronauts in re-used Dragon capsules with reused boosters. (Wikipedia)

name: SpaceX CRS-22
description: NASA Cargo mission to the International Space Station (ISS) on an uncrewed Dragon 2 capsule

name: USSF-44
description: Classified payload totaling 3.75 metric tons. Secondary payload Tetra-1. Will use three new boosters, and first Heavy launch specifically designated to be partially expendable, with two side-boosters targeting a simultaneous landing on droneships. First SpaceX mission directly to geostationary orbit. (Wikipedia)

name: GPS III SV05
description: This will be the fifth launch in GPS Block III, helping keep the Global Positioning System fully operational. The GPS satellite was developed by Lockheed Martin. GPS Block III was originated by the Clinton Administration in 1998.

name: NASA DART
description: The Double Asteroid Redirection Test (DART) will measure the kinetic effects of crashing an impactor into the surface of an asteroid. It will be the first mission to demonstrate asteroid redirect capability.

name: NASA IXPE
description: Three identical NASA telescopes on a single spacecraft, designed to measure X-Rays. The launch contract was awarded to SpaceX for $50.3 million. (Wikipedia)

name: GPS III SV06
description: This will be the sixth launch in GPS Block III, helping keep the Global Positioning System fully operational. The GPS satellite was developed by Lockheed Martin. GPS Block III was originated by the Clinton Administration in 1998.

description: SES launches 7 MEO satellites for O3b connectivity (1/2).

name: Space Adventures Dragon 1
description: SpaceX signed in February 2020, its first commercial flight for a manned spacecraft with the Virginia-based company that had flown seven space tourists between 2001 and 2009. The flight will be around 3 days, up to 5 days, on an elliptical orbit with the apogee three times that of the ISS, and up to four space tourists with a price per seat of around $50M. (Wikipedia)

name: Axiom Space Dragon 1
description: Announced in March 2020, the flight will be the first fully private flight to the ISS. Crew Dragon will carry one Axiom professional astronaut and three private astronauts at around $55 million per seat for a 10-day trip. One seat has already been reserved. (Wikipedia)

name: SmallSat Rideshare 3
description: Rideshare small sat mission

name: CE-SAT I/II Mark II
description: With Spaceflight, launching the Canon Electronics Satellite I (CE-SAT) Mark II, the first mass-production model of CE-SAT I, an Earth-observing satellite. The CE-Sat II has two cameras on the satellite which has different resolutions, also for Earth observation. (Wikipedia)

name: Akash MCNAIR
description: MCNAIR will be launched into a 500 km high sun-synchronous orbit with a 97.8¬∞ inclination. The MCNAIR mission has the purpose of testing the 'GaN-on-Diamond transmitter'. (Wikipedia)

name: Planet Labs Flock-x
description: A constellation of satellites for Earth observation. 20 to 25 micro-satellites will be released during the launch. (Wikipedia)

name: WorldView Legion 2
description: DigitalGlobe WorldView Satellite

name: NASA SWOT
description: American-European satellite intended to measure the surface altitude of water bodies with centimeter-level precision.

name: Korea Pathfinder Lunar Orbiter
description: The first lunar mission for South Korea

name: HEOSAT
description: Space Norway will launch 2 satellites of the Arctic Satellite Broadband Mission (ASBM) system into highly elliptical orbits (apogee 43,000 km, perigee 8,000 km) to provide communication coverage to high latitudes not served by geosynchronous satellites. (Wikipedia)

name: NASA PACE
description: Plankton, Aerosol, Cloud, ocean Ecosystem is a 1.7 tonne, $800 million craft that will orbit at 676 km altitude. It will include the Ocean Color Imager intended to study phytoplankton in the ocean, and two polarimeters for studying properties of clouds, aerosols and the ocean. The launch price was $80.4 million. (Wikipedia)

name: ViaSat-3
description: This mission will inject the satellite in close proximity to geostationary orbit, thus allowing it to be operational faster. Satellites of the ViaSat-3 class use electric propulsion, which requires less fuel for stationkeeping operations over their lifetime, but would need several months to raise its orbit from GTO to GEO. (Wikipedia)

name: Archinaut One
description: Archinaut is an in-space robotic precision manufacturing and assembly system, enabling in-space production and assembly of the backbone structures for large telescopes, repair, augmentation, or repurposing of existing spacecraft, and robotic assembly of new space stations. (Wikipedia)

name: NASA Psyche
description: A Discovery Program mission designed to explore asteroid 16 Psyche. The asteroid is hoped to show what the early solar system looked like and how planets formed. (Wikipedia)
